<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="d29b8e0bb561c551ef6af55da801af76" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> A Treatise on Deck Synergy<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.68)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=5142'>Chris "imrahil327" Schoenthal</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=5142&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 30, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> I’m sure this article has been written before, but due to something that recently happened to me here on DeckTech, I felt that it needed to be restated.  I recently reviewed a deck for which the shadow was just ‘thrown in’-it wasn’t planned out, just a random pile of cards put in so the person could get opinions about their fellowship.  They specifically posted in the strategy, in fact, that they would have just posted a Fellowship but for people who rate down half-decks.  Apparently the person didn’t understand that there was a REASON for this, and that the way he did it didn’t help.<br />
<br />
I gave it 3 stars, because the fellowship wasn’t all that bad, but the Shadow was thoughtless.   I later received a D-mail from the member, very indignant that I’d rated down his deck.  He told me that “LOTR is just two decks shuffled together anyway” and that the Shadow wasn’t particularly important.  I nearly died laughing.<br />
<br />
Sadly, however, this is a fairly common misconception.  Many players make a fellowship, make a shadow, make them the same, and shuffle away, disregarding the possibility that, for one reason or another, their deck will hurt itself more than the opponent.  The top players have realized that this is clearly not the case, and that is one of the many aspects that make Mathieu Brochu, Patrick Malboef, Pat Sullivan, Michael Dalton & co. successful.<br />
<br />
Now-for those of you who have been under the previous misconception, let’s look at it and see what makes it a bad idea.  There are two main areas in which a deck can trip over itself: First, the flow of the deck itself-fast vs. slow fellowships & shadows, and the site path conflicting with one side or the other.<br />
<br />
Let’s look at the second one first, as it is easier dealt with and sometimes avoidable. Other times it only hurts the deck enough to be a nuisance.  One example of such a conflict is having White Mountains, a staple site for Uruk or Moria archery, as well as Sauron, with a Rohan fellowship.  Stables, the Rohan site 3, allows someone to exert to get a steed, then traditionally they are healed by site 4.  However, if it’s a shadow built on wounds, it will exert two MORE people rather than healing the first, giving the opponents shadow a distinct advantage.  Another example is Dauntless Hunter with a Moria Swarm shadow-Moria Swarm can decimate Dauntless, and Cavern Entrance is especially detrimental to the short guys, so often the fellowship can get hurt more by their site than helped.  As I said before though, this is often avoidable by playing a different site, unless it’s a crucial site to the shadow, or the effect on the fellowship is not drastic enough to worry about.<br />
<br />
The other, and more pervasive, issue, is deck flow.  Both throughput (how fast cards get from your deck to your hand/table, etc) and the specifics of the deck (Meant to stop opponent & get a win w. fellowship-usually the job of Nazgul, or kill with the shadow-Typically Moria) can aid or hamper your deck.  Culture can often affect the deck size as well.  Nazgul, for instance, should be run as small as possible, certainly no bigger than 35, and even that’s pushing the limit.  Fell Beast has helped the Nazzies immensely in the cycling area, but they should still be as streamlined as possible.  Moria, on the other hand, can be quite large, as they cycle very quickly due to They Are Coming, recurring Scimitars, etc.  Fellowships should be built accordingly.  Some Fellowships are even meant specifically to maximize the Shadow’s chance of winning.  A perfect example of this is Patrick Malboef’s “Ugliest Fellowship Ever.”  It was not meant to run to site 9, but to get as many minions stacked at the bottom with Dwarf of Erebor & Sneaks, so that by either decking yourself or using Underdeeps of Moria, you could get many more minions out than normally possible.<br />
<br />
Hopefully you’ve learned something from this (rather long) article.  Remember that your Fellowship and Shadow should always be in synch with one another, striving for the same goal at the same time, and that they aren’t just two decks shuffled together!  Feel free to D-Mail me if you have any ideas, suggestion or disagreements!<br />
